{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b8f1b12f-5991-4490-a3c8-eb56d3dc160c","content":"For waits and blocks under load, collect a **Thread Time (Wall Clock) trace** — it captures both on-CPU and off-CPU (blocked/waiting) time, unlike CPU-only traces.\n\n**PerfView command:**\n\n```\nPerfView /threadTime /nogui /accepteula /zip /merge /maxCollectSec:30 collect\n```\n\nKey flags:\n\n| Flag | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `/threadTime` | Enables context-switch & ready-thread events for wall-clock analysis |\n| `/maxCollectSec:30` | Limits collection to 30 s (adjust as needed) |\n| `/zip /merge` | Produces a single portable `.zip` for analysis |\n| `/nogui` | Headless — safe for production servers |\n\n**Analysis:** Open the resulting `.zip` in PerfView → **Thread Time Stacks** → filter to your `dotnet` process → look at `BLOCKED_TIME` and `AWAIT_TIME` nodes to find the contended locks or slow async calls.\n\n**Tip:** If you also want GC and allocation insight, add `/clrEvents:GC+Exception /providers:\"Microsoft-Extensions-Logging\"` to the same command.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ffaae2b-a337-4105-aa34-b2d412087e0c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about performance tracing for an ASP.NET Core .NET 8 app on Windows Server. They want to know which trace to collect for waits/blocks and the PerfView command-line arguments. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"6096:23633C:104CD27:14736DA:69FFDDDB"},"id":"176393a1-61f6-441b-88dd-74a25d797f2a","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:22:45.860Z","parentId":"480c3597-f537-4b42-b949-119754fbe295"}
